english:
  title: Record of the Simplified Armillary Sphere Platform
  author: Kim Don
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the seventh year of Xuande, in the autumn of the seventh month, the sovereign attended the royal lectures and discoursed upon the principles of celestial phenomena. He then addressed the Erudite of the Institute of Worthies, Minister Jeong Inji, saying: "Our Eastern realm lies far beyond the seas, yet in all our undertakings we have faithfully followed the institutions of the Central Kingdom. Only in the instruments for observing the heavens do we find ourselves wanting. Since you already oversee the studies of calendrical calculation, together with Grand Erudite Jeong Cho, investigate the ancient texts and create measuring instruments to complete our astronomical verification. Yet the essential matter lies in determining the height of the North Pole's elevation above the horizon. Therefore, first fashion a simplified armillary sphere and present it."

    Thereupon Minister Jeong Cho and Minister Jeong Inji undertook to study the ancient designs, while Minister of the Central Secretariat Yi Cheon supervised the construction work. They first fashioned a wooden model, determining the North Pole's elevation at thirty-eight degrees, which closely accorded with the measurements recorded in the Yuan histories. Thus they proceeded to cast the instrument in bronze, and upon its completion, Minister of the Ministry of Finance An Sun was commanded to construct a stone platform north of the Gyeonghoeru pavilion in the rear garden—thirty-one feet in height, forty-seven feet in length, and thirty-two feet in breadth, surrounded by stone balustrades, with the simplified armillary sphere mounted upon its summit. A proper measuring table was positioned to its south. On the western side of the platform stood a bronze gnomon five hundred and eight feet tall. From blue stone they fashioned a shadow-measuring scale, its surface inscribed with the marks of chang, chi, cun, and fen, employing shadow-indicators to capture the sun's midday shadow and thereby determine the extremities of the two solar periods' waxing and waning. To the west they erected a small pavilion housing both the celestial sphere and the armillary sphere—the armillary to the east, the sphere to the west.

    The armillary sphere's design has varied across the ages. Following the method detailed in the writings of the Wu masters, they fashioned it from lacquered cloth stretched into a perfect sphere ten feet eight inches and six-tenths in circumference. Across its expanse they drew the degrees and divisions of the entire celestial realm. The equator occupied the center, while the ecliptic traced its path inside and outside the equator by roughly twenty-four degrees on either side. Upon it were distributed all the fixed stars of both the inner and outer spheres. The sun traversed one full rotation daily, advancing one degree, suspended by a cord upon the ecliptic and moving backward one degree each day in harmony with the heavens' motion. The ingenious mechanism that drives the water-powered automation remained concealed from view. These five instruments were fully detailed in the records of antiquity.

    South of the Gyeonghoeru, they erected a pavilion of three bays wherein the water-clock was housed, named the Hall of Reported Hours. Within the eastern bay, two tiers of seats were arranged: on the upper tier sat three deities—one striking the bell to mark the hours, another beating the drum for the watch periods, and a third striking the gong for the divisions. On the lower tier sat twelve deities, each bearing a tablet of the zodiacal signs, requiring no human operation yet sounding of themselves according to the time.

    West of the Hall of Ten Thousand Springs, they built a small pavilion named the Hall of Reverent Respect. Within it they fashioned a mountain from lacquered paper, some seven feet high, containing internal mechanisms. Driven by the jade water-clock, five-colored clouds encircled the sun, rising and setting, while jade maidens rang bells in timely fashion. The guardians of the hours and martial protectors gazed upon one another in perpetual regard, while the four cardinal deities and twelve zodiacal spirits rotated in succession, bowing and rising. On all four sides of the mountain were displayed scenes from the Hymns of Bin and the Four Seasons—thus did the ruler contemplate the hardships of his people's sustenance. An asymmetrical vessel was placed to catch the overflow from the water-clock, thereby illustrating the principles of the heavens' fullness and emptiness.

    Since the simplified armillary sphere, though simpler than the full armillary, proved difficult to rotate, two small versions were fashioned—instruments simplified in form yet equal in function. One was positioned west of the Hall of Ten Thousand Springs; the other was granted to the Bureau of Astronomy. For the common folk, ignorant of time's measure, two forms of the inverted-basin sundial were created, each inscribed with deities of the hours, allowing even the simple-minded to know the time by merely glancing downward. One was placed at the Hyejeong Bridge; another at the south street of the Ancestral Temple.

    Yet measurements could be made only by day. To enable both day and night reckoning, they created the Sun-and-Star Time-Determining Instrument, fashioning four of these devices. One was placed east of the Hall of Ten Thousand Springs, another granted to the Bureau of Astronomy, and two were divided between the eastern and western military commands. Because the Sun-and-Star Time-Determining Instrument proved heavy and inconvenient for military campaigns, a smaller version was also created, differing little in principle.

    Further, they fashioned the Hanging-Pearl Sundial: a base six inches three-tenths in length, with a pillar erected on its northern portion and a pool carved on its southern side. A cross was drawn on the northern part of the base, with a suspended weight hanging from the pillar's crown to correspond with the cross, requiring no water-leveling to achieve perfect balance. One hundred divisions of the day were marked upon a small wheel three inches two-tenths in diameter, the wheel-axle passing obliquely through the pillar. A thin cord passed through the wheel's center, fastened above to the pillar's end and below to the base's southern side. The shadow of this cord upon the marked divisions revealed the hour. On cloudy days, when direct observation proved impossible, a portable water-clock was employed—simple in form and spare in construction—with two vessels, one for pouring and one for receiving water, operated by shifting water during the hours of Rat, Horse, Rabbit, and Rooster.

    Multiple copies of the Small Time-Determining Instrument, Hanging-Pearl Sundial, and portable water-clock were distributed to both military sectors, with others remaining at the Bureau of Astronomy. Since one cannot remain ignorant of the hour while mounted on horseback, they also created the Celestial-Balance Sundial, its design resembling the Hanging-Pearl Sundial save that pools were carved north and south, a pillar was erected at the base's center, and a cord through the pillar's crown could be lifted to align with the south.

    For those who would observe the heavens to determine time, the compass needle was customarily employed, yet this involved human intervention. Therefore, they fashioned the Self-Aligning Sundial, requiring no compass needle while naturally establishing true south and north. Its base measured one foot two inches five-tenths in length, two feet at the ends and one foot eight inches five-tenths at the middle, containing a circular pool two inches six-tenths in diameter with water channels running through both ends and circling the pillar. The northern pillar stood one foot one inch tall; the southern pillar, five inches nine-tenths. Below one inch one-tenth of the north pillar and three inches eight-tenths of the south pillar were axles to receive four-pivot rings whose east-west rotation marked half the celestial degrees from sixteen to one hundred sixty-seven degrees. The inner rings appeared like double hoops while the remainder formed complete circles. A line was inscribed through their centers; the base held a square opening with a sighting tube positioned six feet seven-tenths from its center to support the sighting bar. The bar pierced the double rings above and overlooked the complete rings below, rising and falling to the north and south. A level horizon-ring was installed flush with the south pillar's crown to calibrate the sunrise and sunset at the summer solstice. Below the horizon-ring, a half-circle was positioned horizontally, its interior marked with daylight divisions corresponding to the square opening. A cross was drawn on the base's northern portion with a weight suspended from the north axis's end to align with the cross, thereby achieving perfect leveling. When the sighting bar was directed to the sun's degrees of declination for any given day and the solar image entered the opening as a perfect circle, one need only look through the square opening downward upon the half-circle's divisions to determine true south and know the hour with perfect accuracy.

    Fifteen instruments in total were created, ten of which were cast in bronze. After several years of labor, the work was completed in the spring of the Muo year. The authorities requested that a record be made for posterity. Thus was I commanded, having consulted upon these designs, to set down this account.

    I reflect that the essential matter of establishing the calendar lies in observing the heavens, and the essential matter of observing the heavens lies in the instruments. Therefore did the sage-king Yao command Xi and He to trace the courses of sun, moon, and stars, and did the sage-king Shun employ the celestial sphere to order the seven celestial bodies. Truly, the reverent regard for heaven and the diligent care for the people cannot be delayed. From the Han and Tang dynasties onward, each age possessed such instruments, some successful, others flawed, defying easy enumeration. Only those created by Guo Shoujing of the Yuan—the simplified armillary sphere, the observation sphere, the shadow-measuring scale and others—deserve the name of ingenious.

    Yet in our Eastern realm, such creations remained unknown until heaven opened its favor and learning began to flourish. Our sovereign, possessing the qualities of sage and sage-king, moved by reverent respect and finding moment in the midst of myriad duties to recognize the imperfection of our calendar calculations, commanded their verification. Perceiving the incompleteness of our astronomical apparatus, he ordered its creation. What wisdom could surpass that of Yao and Shun?

    In creating these instruments, his majesty did not limit himself to one or two but extended to many varieties, ever prepared for comparison. In their design, he did not merely imitate the ancients but determined all through his sacred wisdom, each achieving utmost refinement. Even Guo Shoujing of the Yuan could not have surpassed such artistry.

    Ah! Having verified the calendar of established time and having fashioned the instruments for observing the heavens, he thereby serves the celestial order above and brings diligence to the people's affairs below. The supreme humanity of our sovereign in opening the nature of things to accomplish his duties, and his supreme dedication in encouraging agriculture and cherishing its foundations, represents an unprecedented glory in our Eastern realm. This achievement shall endure alongside these lofty platforms for endless ages to come.
  footnotes:
    - The Simplified Armillary Sphere (簡儀) was a major astronomical instrument developed during the Yuan dynasty by the renowned astronomer Guo Shoujing. It was simpler and more practical than the traditional full armillary sphere while maintaining equivalent functionality.
    - The North Pole's elevation above the horizon (北極出地) refers to the celestial elevation of Polaris, a critical measurement in establishing accurate latitude for astronomical calculations and calendar reform.
    - The Water-Clock (漏器) represents one of East Asia's most sophisticated timekeeping technologies, using calibrated water flow through vessels to measure hours, particularly important for nighttime observation when sundials were ineffective.
    - Xi and He (羲和), legendary figures in Chinese mythology, were traditionally credited by Confucian scholars as having established the systems for tracking celestial bodies under the sage-king Yao.
